The illegal ivory trade poses a grave threat to African elephants, with only 10% of contraband being detected.
Recent studies show a resurgence in illicit trade, putting the species at renewed risk of extinction.
DNA testing has helped identify the origin of poached tusks, aiding efforts to curb the black market.
However, the challenge lies in enforcing strong regulations to protect these majestic creatures.
Countries like Kenya and Mali advocate for a complete ban on ivory trade, while others seek sustainable conservation methods.
The future of African elephants hangs in the balance, requiring global cooperation and decisive action.
